  "text": "If one takes α = β, CS gravity is recovered, in which case we exactly have c A T = 1 and only the amplitude is modified through ν A . This agrees with the previous argument [CITATION_1] . In general parity-violating gravity, however, the propagation speed is also modified. Note that since the sign of ν A is determined by λ A , ν R and ν L always have opposite signs. That is, if the amplitude of one polarization mode is enhanced, the other is suppressed. This is also true for (c A T ) 2 − 1: If one polarization mode is superluminal, then the other is subluminal.",
